1
00:00:08,200 --> 00:00:10,266
Welcome to Love Lab!

2
00:00:10,266 --> 00:00:12,300
We offer all kinds of services.

3
00:00:12,633 --> 00:00:14,166
No matter how tough,

4
00:00:14,500 --> 00:00:17,200
unusual, or messy the task.

5
00:00:17,200 --> 00:00:19,333
As the number-one employee,

6
00:00:19,333 --> 00:00:20,468
I can manage absolutely everything.

7
00:01:10,300 --> 00:01:11,633
What are you doing?

8
00:01:13,066 --> 00:01:14,433
My gorgeous sister.

9
00:01:14,433 --> 00:01:15,633
Oh, it's just you, Claire

10
00:01:20,200 --> 00:01:22,066
Thanks for the compliment.

11
00:01:22,900 --> 00:01:24,733
But since when am I your older sister?

12
00:01:25,300 --> 00:01:27,933
My mom is just older than yours, that's all.

13
00:01:33,800 --> 00:01:35,333
By the way, how come you're here so early today?

14
00:01:36,966 --> 00:01:39,866
The AC at my place is broken,

15
00:01:39,866 --> 00:01:41,566
and it's freezing here.

16
00:01:41,566 --> 00:01:43,200
It saves on the electricity bill.

17
00:01:43,200 --> 00:01:45,766
Right, right.

18
00:01:46,400 --> 00:01:47,966
But it's good that you're here.

19
00:01:47,966 --> 00:01:49,933
You don't have any appointments this morning anyway.

20
00:01:56,500 --> 00:01:58,133
Can you help me out with something?

21
00:01:58,900 --> 00:02:00,233
Help with what?

22
00:02:00,800 --> 00:02:01,666
No way.

23
00:02:02,966 --> 00:02:04,433
That's your job, not mine.

24
00:02:06,266 --> 00:02:08,200
Please help me.

25
00:02:09,133 --> 00:02:11,433
This task is a bit heavy.

26
00:02:12,400 --> 00:02:13,266
What kind of job is it?

27
00:02:13,266 --> 00:02:16,166
Usually, you only take jobs like

28
00:02:16,166 --> 00:02:17,633
taking grandmas to see the doctor,

29
00:02:17,933 --> 00:02:19,366
reading storybooks to kids,

30
00:02:19,366 --> 00:02:20,600
or walking dogs.

31
00:02:20,600 --> 00:02:22,533
Alright, stop talking.

32
00:02:23,000 --> 00:02:24,700
This one is really heavy, seriously.

33
00:02:25,400 --> 00:02:27,500
Aunt Somporn from Alley 4

34
00:02:27,500 --> 00:02:30,200
hired me to help carry  "Thang Gas" (Gas Tank).

35
00:02:30,200 --> 00:02:31,333
He's not feeling well.

36
00:02:31,933 --> 00:02:33,900
He sprained his leg,

37
00:02:33,900 --> 00:02:36,333
and he weighs 40 kilograms.

38
00:02:36,933 --> 00:02:37,900
Heavy, right?

39
00:02:38,433 --> 00:02:41,033
Whoa, that really is heavy.

40
00:02:47,333 --> 00:02:49,466
Alright, alright. I'll help.

41
00:02:50,733 --> 00:02:53,033
Thanks, Grace, my best friend.

42
00:02:54,900 --> 00:02:55,533
Let's go then.

43
00:02:55,533 --> 00:02:57,644
Come on, hurry. He's waiting.

44
00:03:07,880 --> 00:03:10,520
Kitty  Nunthaphuck Aranyakasemsuk

45
00:03:11,743 --> 00:03:14,363
Punch Naphassanan Kalaphan

46
00:03:15,538 --> 00:03:18,814
Bmine Jiratchaya Komontut

47
00:03:44,800 --> 00:03:46,000
I believe you now.

48
00:03:47,733 --> 00:03:50,833
Is that Thang Gas a puppy or a piglet?

49
00:03:51,933 --> 00:03:53,233
My back is about to break from carrying him.

50
00:03:54,500 --> 00:03:56,433
Tell me about it.

51
00:03:59,033 --> 00:04:00,700
Good thing you came to help.

52
00:04:01,333 --> 00:04:03,866
Otherwise, if it were just me, I'd definitely be dead.

53
00:04:41,866 --> 00:04:44,900
Welcome to Love Lab.

54
00:04:44,900 --> 00:04:47,800
We offer all kinds of services.

55
00:04:50,066 --> 00:04:52,600
Are you interested in any particular service?

56
00:04:57,100 --> 00:04:59,966
Hello, I'm Eris. I'm a novelist.

57
00:05:00,400 --> 00:05:02,233
I usually write mystery and suspense.

58
00:05:02,233 --> 00:05:05,000
But my publisher wants me to write a romance novel,

59
00:05:05,000 --> 00:05:06,333
the kind that people love to read.

60
00:05:06,866 --> 00:05:08,500
But I have absolutely no experience in this area,

61
00:05:08,533 --> 00:05:10,033
so I'd like to ask for some help.

62
00:05:10,300 --> 00:05:13,133
Then what brings you here?

63
00:05:14,066 --> 00:05:15,400
We don't do scriptwriting.

64
00:05:16,366 --> 00:05:17,666
I understand.

65
00:05:17,666 --> 00:05:19,433
I'm not hiring you to write a script.

66
00:05:19,433 --> 00:05:21,433
I'm here to gather information to write my novel.

67
00:05:23,500 --> 00:05:25,600
In that case, you're more than welcome.

68
00:05:26,500 --> 00:05:29,333
I'm Cher, the shop owner here.

69
00:05:30,666 --> 00:05:31,766
Nice to meet you.

70
00:05:32,066 --> 00:05:36,533
And this is Claire, my business partner.

71
00:05:36,533 --> 00:05:38,166
She's my cousin.

72
00:05:39,566 --> 00:05:43,433
Please take a seat over there and wait for a moment.

73
00:05:56,400 --> 00:05:57,500
Please, have a seat.

74
00:06:06,766 --> 00:06:10,100
The only excitement I get right now is

75
00:06:10,100 --> 00:06:13,233
connecting complex cases so the readers can't guess what's coming.

76
00:06:13,233 --> 00:06:15,833
Like when the culprit is revealed or the murderer is punished.

77
00:06:15,833 --> 00:06:17,100
So, I don't understand...

78
00:06:17,333 --> 00:06:21,900
how it feels to have a partner in romance novels.

79
00:06:22,400 --> 00:06:25,566
Please calm down. I understand completely.

80
00:06:27,533 --> 00:06:29,500
I'd like to hire a staff member to help act out

81
00:06:29,500 --> 00:06:32,233
and simulate romantic scenes that people love.

82
00:06:32,233 --> 00:06:36,166
I want to capture those feelings and information for my writing.

83
00:06:36,166 --> 00:06:37,166
Something like that.

84
00:06:38,300 --> 00:06:39,100
Okay.

85
00:06:44,366 --> 00:06:45,400
Well...

86
00:06:46,800 --> 00:06:51,866
Here she is. This is Claire, Love Lab's number-one employee.

87
00:06:52,166 --> 00:06:56,600
No matter if you want a scene that's sweet romance,

88
00:06:56,600 --> 00:07:00,200
making the heart race, or heart-fluttering,

89
00:07:00,200 --> 00:07:01,633
she can handle it all for you.

90
00:07:04,166 --> 00:07:06,300
Hey, ask me first, Cher!

91
00:07:06,300 --> 00:07:07,366
Come on...

92
00:07:07,900 --> 00:07:09,566
How about this person?

93
00:07:14,433 --> 00:07:19,733
And would you like to rent her by the hour,

94
00:07:19,733 --> 00:07:21,433
half-day, or full-day, Ms. Eris?

95
00:07:21,866 --> 00:07:22,933
If it's a full day, right now...

96
00:07:22,933 --> 00:07:24,400
One hour.

97
00:07:26,700 --> 00:07:28,633
One hour, then.

98
00:07:29,233 --> 00:07:30,300
Okay.

99
00:07:31,666 --> 00:07:32,866
Please wait a moment.

100
00:07:56,400 --> 00:07:57,366
Oops! I'm sorry.

101
00:07:59,466 --> 00:08:02,633
It's fine. Can we start now?

102
00:08:04,533 --> 00:08:06,300
According to romance novel theory,

103
00:08:06,300 --> 00:08:09,733
80% of falling-in-love scenes happen in a park.

104
00:08:11,000 --> 00:08:13,966
Claire, let's start with the first scene.

105
00:08:14,566 --> 00:08:16,333
"Accidental Love Bump."

106
00:08:18,100 --> 00:08:20,100
What do I need to do, Ms. Writer?

107
00:08:20,633 --> 00:08:24,300
I'll be standing over here, reading my iPad.

108
00:08:24,300 --> 00:08:27,433
As for you, walk from over there while looking at your phone,

109
00:08:27,433 --> 00:08:28,733
and then bump into me.

110
00:08:28,966 --> 00:08:29,733
Let's try it.

111
00:08:47,233 --> 00:08:50,366
The force of the impact increases the heart rate.

112
00:08:50,366 --> 00:08:52,800
I can smell sweat mixed with...

113
00:08:53,433 --> 00:08:55,300
a faint smell of dog.

114
00:08:57,233 --> 00:08:58,133
Claire.

115
00:08:59,066 --> 00:09:00,866
Please move closer for a moment.

116
00:09:01,300 --> 00:09:02,766
This angle is just right.

117
00:09:03,433 --> 00:09:06,366
I want to see the camera angle that romance novels describe as...

118
00:09:06,800 --> 00:09:08,966
"The sunlight hits the face,

119
00:09:08,966 --> 00:09:11,933
and their eyes lock as if under a spell."

120
00:09:12,700 --> 00:09:13,866
What is that like?

121
00:09:32,133 --> 00:09:33,900
Tuck my hair behind my ear.

122
00:09:34,933 --> 00:09:35,566
Hurry.

123
00:09:38,566 --> 00:09:43,000
One... Two... Three... Four...

124
00:09:44,700 --> 00:09:47,700
Five... Six... Seven...

125
00:09:47,700 --> 00:09:48,833
What are you doing?

126
00:09:49,466 --> 00:09:51,100
It's "The 8-second eye contact theory."

127
00:09:51,533 --> 00:09:54,500
They say if you can maintain eye contact for 8 seconds,

128
00:09:54,500 --> 00:09:56,233
it can make us fall in love.

129
00:09:57,966 --> 00:10:02,166
Heart rate is 110 beats per minute.

130
00:10:02,166 --> 00:10:03,666
Facial muscles are starting to twitch.

131
00:10:04,866 --> 00:10:06,000
To think a person can actually

132
00:10:06,000 --> 00:10:09,333
lose their mind at a distance of just 2 cm...

133
00:10:09,333 --> 00:10:10,200
Hey... you...

134
00:10:10,200 --> 00:10:12,533
But touch has an effect too.

135
00:10:12,533 --> 00:10:13,000
You...

136
00:10:13,000 --> 00:10:14,033
Atmosphere.

137
00:10:14,033 --> 00:10:15,033
Ms. Eris.

138
00:10:15,633 --> 00:10:16,300
Yes?

139
00:10:16,866 --> 00:10:18,333
The one hour is up.

140
00:10:18,933 --> 00:10:21,033
Let's part ways here.

141
00:10:21,033 --> 00:10:23,266
Oh, right, the hour is up.

142
00:10:24,366 --> 00:10:26,633
Time's up. I'll take my leave now.

143
00:10:38,966 --> 00:10:42,200
Finally, I can wash off this Thang Gas smell.

144
00:10:42,200 --> 00:10:43,800
What a crazy writer.

145
00:10:53,533 --> 00:10:55,866
Claire, look at what I sent you on LINE.

146
00:11:02,766 --> 00:11:05,500
I knew Ms. Eris's name sounded familiar.

147
00:11:05,933 --> 00:11:08,266
Plus, she said she writes mystery novels.

148
00:11:09,900 --> 00:11:10,566
What?

149
00:11:11,933 --> 00:11:14,700
There could be many writers with that name, right?

150
00:11:15,000 --> 00:11:16,866
It's definitely her.

151
00:11:17,700 --> 00:11:21,233
Earlier, when she opened her iPad to show those scenes...

152
00:11:21,633 --> 00:11:24,700
I saw the cover of the novel we've been reading.

153
00:11:27,233 --> 00:11:29,500
My inner fangirl is so fulfilled!

154
00:11:31,133 --> 00:11:34,533
But I don't feel fulfilled at all.

155
00:11:34,533 --> 00:11:36,566
Oh, a customer is here. I have to go.

156
00:11:36,566 --> 00:11:37,666
Let's gossip more later.

157
00:11:38,333 --> 00:11:38,900
Hey!

158
00:11:48,766 --> 00:11:51,500
Cher! That's cold!

159
00:11:52,066 --> 00:11:54,033
Well, you complained it was hot.

160
00:11:54,033 --> 00:11:55,133
Are you cooler now?

161
00:11:56,666 --> 00:11:58,033
Move your legs out!

162
00:12:07,800 --> 00:12:09,233
So, how was it?

163
00:12:09,233 --> 00:12:11,366
Going with your favorite author.

164
00:12:11,366 --> 00:12:12,233
Was it wonderful?

165
00:12:12,933 --> 00:12:13,800
Wonderful?

166
00:12:14,900 --> 00:12:18,666
Are you sure this person is the real Ms. Eris?

167
00:12:19,233 --> 00:12:20,233
A million percent.

168
00:12:22,333 --> 00:12:23,166
Why?

169
00:12:24,233 --> 00:12:27,133
My dream author is completely ruined.

170
00:12:29,033 --> 00:12:32,666
The image I imagined is totally different from this woman.

171
00:12:32,666 --> 00:12:34,933
She is out of her mind!

172
00:12:34,933 --> 00:12:35,933
Stop it.

173
00:12:36,233 --> 00:12:37,400
You shouldn't gossip about customers.

174
00:12:44,233 --> 00:12:45,933
Let's go home.

175
00:12:46,666 --> 00:12:47,500
Come on, hurry.

176
00:12:47,500 --> 00:12:49,266
Let's grab something to eat too.

177
00:12:49,266 --> 00:12:50,600
I'm starving.

178
00:12:51,433 --> 00:12:53,633
All my energy was drained by Thang Gas.

179
00:12:53,866 --> 00:12:54,733
Let's go.

180
00:12:58,833 --> 00:12:59,733
Let's go.

181
00:13:32,333 --> 00:13:35,766
"An Hour of Trial Love"

182
00:14:21,166 --> 00:14:22,400
Hello, Ms. Eris.

183
00:14:23,100 --> 00:14:23,800
How did it go?

184
00:14:23,800 --> 00:14:25,366
Did our number-one employee

185
00:14:25,366 --> 00:14:29,200
help simulate the romantic scene exactly as you wanted?

186
00:14:30,200 --> 00:14:32,700
In terms of structure, it was acceptable.

187
00:14:32,966 --> 00:14:35,366
But regarding the psychological chemical reaction,

188
00:14:35,366 --> 00:14:37,166
I didn't get any data.

189
00:14:38,233 --> 00:14:40,133
Hey... you were staring at me

190
00:14:40,133 --> 00:14:42,200
like you were interrogating a suspect.

191
00:14:42,733 --> 00:14:45,366
Who could possibly feel enchanted by that, Ms. Writer?

192
00:14:47,466 --> 00:14:49,233
Claire is just like that.

193
00:14:49,766 --> 00:14:50,666
Anyway...

194
00:14:51,133 --> 00:14:55,966
How many hours of service would you like to use today, Ms. Eris?

195
00:14:56,366 --> 00:14:58,100
Today, I'd like two hours, please.

196
00:14:58,533 --> 00:15:00,100
I have several other sweet scenes

197
00:15:00,100 --> 00:15:01,666
that I still don't quite understand.

198
00:15:02,133 --> 00:15:05,633
Especially the scene they call the Pocky Game.

199
00:15:06,133 --> 00:15:06,833
Wait...

200
00:15:08,000 --> 00:15:09,133
The Pocky Game?

201
00:15:09,933 --> 00:15:14,233
The one where they hold a Pocky stick in their mouths

202
00:15:14,233 --> 00:15:15,700
from opposite ends until their lips almost touch?

203
00:15:15,966 --> 00:15:16,666
Yes.

204
00:15:17,033 --> 00:15:17,966
In romance novels,

205
00:15:17,966 --> 00:15:20,233
this scene usually makes the characters' hearts beat the fastest,

206
00:15:20,233 --> 00:15:21,333
completely out of control.

207
00:15:21,533 --> 00:15:23,266
But I still don't understand

208
00:15:23,266 --> 00:15:24,566
how just a single snack stick...

209
00:15:25,000 --> 00:15:28,500
can make the adrenaline in the body surge that much.

210
00:15:29,366 --> 00:15:30,833
But don't you worry.

211
00:15:31,433 --> 00:15:33,333
I brought Pocky today.

212
00:15:34,166 --> 00:15:36,566
So, get yourself and your lips ready.

213
00:15:37,166 --> 00:15:37,666
Hey...

214
00:15:38,900 --> 00:15:40,000
Are you serious?

215
00:15:40,600 --> 00:15:42,400
Go right ahead, Ms. Eris.

216
00:15:43,100 --> 00:15:44,900
Our number-one employee...

217
00:15:45,966 --> 00:15:48,033
is fully ready to serve you.

218
00:15:55,600 --> 00:15:56,933
I’ve done my research.

219
00:15:59,833 --> 00:16:02,933
In this scene, the crucial factor isn't the distance or the atmosphere.

220
00:16:03,333 --> 00:16:06,900
It's the "pressure" as the snack gets shorter and shorter.
